Ah, I see what you want: a **common `mapCourse` method** to avoid repeating the mapping logic in every endpoint. This is a good idea—it keeps your code DRY (Don’t Repeat Yourself). You can create a **utility method** that converts your internal `Course` object to the JAXB-generated `CourseDetails`.

Here’s how you can do it:

---

### 1️⃣ Add a `mapCourse` method

You can put it **inside the endpoint class** or, better, in a **common utility class** if you want to reuse it in other endpoints.

**Option 1: Inside the endpoint class**

```java
private CourseDetails mapCourse(Course course) {
    CourseDetails courseDetails = new CourseDetails();
    courseDetails.setId(course.getId());
    courseDetails.setName(course.getName());
    courseDetails.setDescription(course.getDescription());
    return courseDetails;
}
```

**Then you can rewrite your methods like this:**

```java
@PayloadRoot(namespace="http://example.com/courses", localPart="GetCourseDetailRequest")
@ResponsePayload
public GetCourseDetailResponse getCourseDetail(@RequestPayload GetCourseDetailRequest request) {
    GetCourseDetailResponse response = new GetCourseDetailResponse();

    Course course = Service.getCoursebyID(request.getId());
    if (course != null) {
        response.setCourseDetails(mapCourse(course));
    }

    return response;
}

@PayloadRoot(namespace="http://example.com/courses", localPart="GetAllCourseDetailRequest")
@ResponsePayload
public GetAllCourseDetailResponse getAllCourseDetail(@RequestPayload GetAllCourseDetailRequest request) {
    GetAllCourseDetailResponse response = new GetAllCourseDetailResponse();

    List<Course> coursesList = Service.getCourses();
    for (Course c : coursesList) {
        response.getCourseDetails().add(mapCourse(c));
    }

    return response;
}
```

---

### 2️⃣ Option 2: Common utility class

Create a **separate helper class** (recommended if multiple endpoints need mapping):

```java
package com.example.coursemgmt2.utils;

import courses.Course;
import com.example.coursemgmt2.coursemgmt2.soap.CourseDetails;

public class CourseMapper {
    public static CourseDetails mapCourse(Course course) {
        CourseDetails details = new CourseDetails();
        details.setId(course.getId());
        details.setName(course.getName());
        details.setDescription(course.getDescription());
        return details;
    }
}
```

Then in your endpoint:

```java
import com.example.coursemgmt2.utils.CourseMapper;

response.setCourseDetails(CourseMapper.mapCourse(course));
```

---

✅ **Benefits of using `mapCourse`:**

1. Avoids repeating the mapping logic in multiple methods.
2. Centralizes mapping logic (easy to update later).
3. Cleaner and more readable endpoint code.

